Ch7: A model workflow

This section focuses on building modeling workflows, which bundle the pre-processing of data and defining model specifications into a single step to aid in organization. First, lets set up the libraries and data well need for the notebook.

# Libraries
library(pacman)
p_load(tidyverse, tidymodels, patchwork, broom)

# Prepare input data
data(ames, package = "modeldata")
ames <- ames %>% mutate(Sale_Price = log10(Sale_Price))

set.seed(123)
ames_split <- initial_split(ames, prop = 0.8, strata = Sale_Price)
ames_train <- training(ames_split)
ames_test <- testing(ames_split)

# Build the linear regression model specification 
lm_mod <- linear_reg() %>% 
  set_engine("lm")

In addition to pre-processing, the model workflow helps to organize post-processing steps that may be required to evaluate and optimize model fit, like optimizing the probability cutoff for classification problems. Now well build the workflow object, add the linear regression model specification we defined above, and add a model formula.

# Build the workflow
(lm_workflow <- 
  workflow() %>% 
  add_model(lm_mod) %>% 
  add_formula(Sale_Price ~ Longitude + Latitude))
 Workflow

# Fit the model with the workflow
(lm_fit <- fit(lm_workflow, ames_train))

# We can easily update the formula in the workflow
lm_fit %>% 
  update_formula(Sale_Price ~ Longitude)

Instead of passing a formula to the workflow, we can add variables explicitly using add_variables().

(lm_workflow <- lm_workflow %>% 
  remove_formula() %>% 
  add_variables(outcome = Sale_Price, predictors = c(Latitude, Longitude)))
 Workflow 
Preprocessor: Variables
Model: linear_reg()

 Preprocessor 
Outcomes: Sale_Price
Predictors: c(Latitude, Longitude)

 Model 
Linear Regression Model Specification (regression)

Computational engine: lm

If we want to build a series of models to evaluate model fit with different predictions, we can use workflow sets, as illustrated below.

# Define list of variables
location <- list(
  longitude = Sale_Price ~ Longitude,
  latitude = Sale_Price ~ Latitude,
  coords = Sale_Price ~ Latitude + Longitude,
  neighborhood = Sale_Price ~ Neighborhood
)

# Build workflow set with the locations and linear model specification
(location_models <- workflow_set(preproc = location, models = list(lm = lm_mod)))
NA

We can extract individual workflows using the extract_workflow() function.

extract_workflow(location_models, id = "coords_lm")
 Workflow

Model: linear_reg()

 Preprocessor

Now well fit each model and look at he results.

(location_models <- location_models %>% 
  mutate(fit = map(info, ~ fit(.x$workflow[[1]], ames_train))))
